The gas limit in #Ethereum achieves the same purpose of the size limit in #Bitcoin.

They preserve #Decentralization through limiting the computational work needs to be done by nodes.

Gas is the fundamental unit of computation in #Ethereum; which means that one computational step requires one unit of gas.

For example, a simple #ETH transfer would require 21,000 units of gas to be executed (21,000 computational steps).

To preserve decentralization in #Ethereum, i.e. limit the computational work that needs to be done by nodes; transactions must specify how much computation they would need to be executed.

This is done through: Gas.
In #Ethereum, a transaction may be small in size, but trigger a large amount of computation through a contract (e.g. contract that calculates one million hashes).
